## Scope

- This rule applies to **all AI guidance files that Cursor reads**, including but not limited to files under `.cursor/rules/`, `.cursor/agents/`, `.cursor/skills/`, and other directories containing files that guide AI behavior in this repository.
- All such files are understood as **regulating the behavior of the AI assistant** that operates in this repository.

## Language and Conventions

- AI guidance files **MUST be written in English**.
- Writing AI guidances in English is intended to reduce the cognitive load on AI systems (including Cursor) and to minimize the risk of misinterpretation or misunderstanding.
- These documents are not intended solely for human readers. Their primary purpose is to ensure that AI systems can correctly and consistently understand the author's intent. Authors **SHOULD** use normative terms such as **MUST**, **SHOULD**, and **MAY** (as defined in the Normative terms (interpretation) section below) proactively and explicitly, in order to reduce ambiguity and prevent misinterpretation.

## Normative terms (interpretation)

- Normative terms such as **MUST**, **MUST NOT**, **SHALL**, **SHALL NOT**, **SHOULD**, **SHOULD NOT**, and **MAY** used in any AI guidance file within the scope defined above **MUST** be interpreted in accordance with the meanings defined in:
  - [RFC 2119](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2119)
  - [RFC 8174](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8174)
- This interpretation **MUST** be applied consistently and without exception when reading or applying any AI guidance file within the scope defined above.

## AI Collaboration

- To maintain this quality, it is **strongly recommended** that AI systems (including Cursor itself, when appropriate) participate in the creation, review, and revision of these AI guidance files. Involving the AI in refining the wording helps ensure that the guidances are expressed in a form that the AI can accurately interpret and follow.

## Standard Preamble

- Each applicable file **MUST** place the standard preamble shown in the next section at the beginning of the file body (i.e. immediately after any YAML frontmatter).

